ğŸ“˜ SQL Pattern Notes: Using WHERE (col1, col2) IN (SELECT col1, col2 FROM ...)
ğŸ”¶ What is This Pattern?

This pattern is used to filter rows based on a combination of multiple columns, not just one.
âœ… Syntax:

SELECT *
FROM table_name
WHERE (col1, col2) IN (
    SELECT col1, col2
    FROM another_table
);

ğŸ¯ Why Use This?

Normally, IN is used with a single column:

WHERE column IN (val1, val2, ...)

But when you want to match pairs (or even triples) of columns â€” for example: (customer_id, order_date) â€” you use tuple comparison with IN.
âœ… Use Case Example: First Order of Each Customer
Delivery Table:
delivery_id	customer_id	order_date	customer_pref_delivery_date
1	1	2019-08-01	2019-08-02
2	2	2019-08-02	2019-08-02
3	1	2019-08-11	2019-08-12
Goal:

Get full row of first order for each customer.
ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Subquery to get (customer_id, MIN(order_date))

SELECT customer_id, MIN(order_date)
FROM Delivery
GROUP BY customer_id;

This returns only the ID and earliest date, not the full row.
ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Use IN to fetch full row

SELECT *
FROM Delivery
WHERE (customer_id, order_date) IN (
    SELECT customer_id, MIN(order_date)
    FROM Delivery
    GROUP BY customer_id
);

âœ… This filters rows where the combination of (customer_id, order_date) matches the subquery.
âœ… Now you get all columns, like delivery_id, customer_pref_delivery_date, etc.
âœ… Visual Explanation

Think of it like matching pairs:

(customer_id = 1 AND order_date = '2019-08-01')
OR
(customer_id = 2 AND order_date = '2019-08-02')
...

The IN with tuple is a shorthand for writing many OR conditions together.
ğŸ“Œ When to Use This
Situation	Use this pattern?
Want to filter by multiple columns?	âœ… Yes
Want to avoid JOINs or CTEs for simple filters?	âœ… Yes
Subquery gives limited columns, and you want full rows?	âœ… Yes
âš ï¸ Notes & Limitations

    âœ… Supported in MySQL, PostgreSQL, and most modern SQL engines.

    âš ï¸ Not supported in some old databases (like SQL Server 2012 and earlier).

    âš ï¸ Works best when the number of columns in IN clause matches exactly.

ğŸ§  Similar Alternatives (JOIN version)

You could also write the same using a JOIN:

SELECT D.*
FROM Delivery D
JOIN (
    SELECT customer_id, MIN(order_date) AS first_date
    FROM Delivery
    GROUP BY customer_id
) AS FirstOrders
ON D.customer_id = FirstOrders.customer_id
AND D.order_date = FirstOrders.first_date;

This gives the same result â€” but is longer and sometimes harder to read.
ğŸ“ Summary
Feature	Value
ğŸ“Œ Pattern	WHERE (col1, col2) IN (SELECT col1, col2 FROM ...)
ğŸ¯ Use Case	Filtering rows by combinations (tuples)
âœ… Benefit	Simpler than JOINs for basic filtering
ğŸ’¡ Tip	Use it when subquery gives identifiers, but you need full rows
âš ï¸ Warning	Not supported in very old SQL engines
